statement.p:
 This exercise guides you through the proof of Lemma \ref{lemma-loop}. Let G be a multigraph rooted at vertex x with a loop edge  e incident with vertex y. Let H be the multigraph obtained by replacing this loop by a twig edge f from y to a new vertex z. You will show that the Green Hackenbush game position G \oplus H satisfies \g(G \oplus H) = 0.





\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.8]


\draw[dashed] (-2,0) -- (8,0);

\foreach \i in {0,5}
{

\begin{scope}[shift={(\i,0)}]



\draw (0,1.3) ellipse (.8 and 1.5);

\draw[fill] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (.7, 2) circle (3pt);




\node at (.2,.4) {x};
\node at (.3,1.7) {y};


\end{scope}
}

\draw[thick] (.95, 2.15) circle (.25);

\node at (1.45,2.15) {e};

\draw[thick] (5.7, 2) -- (6.4, 2.2);
\draw[fill] (6.4, 2.2) circle (3pt);

\node at (6.05,2.5) {f};

\node at (0,-.75) {G};

\node at (5,-.75) {H};

\end{tikzpicture}










 Suppose that Left hacks the loop e in G. What should Right do? How do you know that this results in a \Ppos?






 Suppose that Left hacks  an edge in G that disconnects the loop e from the root of G. What should Right do?






 Use induction on the number of edges m in G to prove that if Left hacks an edge in G that does not disconnect the loop e from the root, then Right has a move in H to create a \Ppos. Your base case is m=0, in which G consists of a single root vertex x with no edges. (This means that for the base case, we have y=x since this is the only vertex in G.)






 What if Left makes his first move in H instead of in G?






 Explain why \g(G \oplus H) = 0 means that \g(G) = \g(H).

